            "answer_text": "Three periods in a row is called an ellipsis. It can be used to show that something has been left out, or that a sentence is unfinished. When you use an ellipsis at the end of a sentence, or if you omit more a whole sentence or more, a fourth period follows as end punctuation. Ex: \"Well,\" said Martha, \"If you really want to know....\" Many people overuse ellipses rather than punctuate properly. http://www.kentlaw.edu/academics/lrw/grinker/LwtaEllipses.htm http://grammar.ccc.commnet.edu/grammar/marks/ellipsis.htm ",
